Though the Cat‚Äôs Eye nebula (NGC 6543) was one of the first planetary nebulae to be discovered, it is one of the meow-st complex ones ever seen. @nasahubble captured its complexities in great detail here, highlighting a bullseye pattern of eleven or more concentric rings, or shells. Each ‚Äòring‚Äô is actually the edge of a spherical bubble seen projected onto the sky. Observations suggest the star ejected its mass in a series of pulses at 1,500-year intervals. These convulsions created dust shells, each of which contain as much mass as all the planets in our solar system combined.
 
Planetary nebulae are one cat-egory of nebulae. They got their name because when they were first observed through early telescopes, they resembled planets. However, a planetary nebula is the final stage in the evolution of a star that is similar to our Sun.
 
Several explanations have been proposed for the bullseye patterns seen around planetary nebulae like the Cat‚Äôs Eye, including: cycles of magnetic activity somewhat like the Sun's sunspot cycle; the action of a companion star orbiting around the dying star; and stellar pulsations. Another school of thought is that the material is ejected smoothly from the star, and the rings are created later due to waves forming in the outflowing material. Further observations and more theoretical studies are needed to decide between these and other purr-tential explanations.
